{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17623529","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17623529"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:12:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:12:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16866"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16866","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16866"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.69,0,0,0.22,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9556"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68696"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9556","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9556"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16866"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54153"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9875"},{"type":"tags","id":"10324"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22569"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22573"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68696","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68696"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe body maintains homeostasis through various sensing mechanisms that detect changes in blood composition.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary stimulus for the peripheral chemoreceptors of the carotid and aortic bodies?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Decreased arterial oxygen","Increased blood potassium","Decreased blood glucose","Increased blood pH","Decreased carbon dioxide"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased arterial oxygen\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary stimulus for peripheral chemoreceptors located in the carotid and aortic bodies. These specialised cells are most sensitive to changes in arterial oxygen tension, though they also respond to changes in carbon dioxide and pH to a lesser extent. In contrast, the central chemoreceptors (located in the medulla of the brain) are primarily responsible for sensing and increasing ventilation in response to increased carbon dioxide/H+ ions and show no response to decreased oxygen tension in the blood.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased carbon dioxide\u003C/strong\u003E - peripheral chemoreceptors respond to increased carbon dioxide levels\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased blood pH\u003C/strong\u003E - the carotid bodies respond to increased H+ ion concentration (which indicates decreased, not increased pH)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased blood potassium\u003C/strong\u003E - peripheral chemoreceptors do not directly respond to changes in potassium levels\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased blood glucose\u003C/strong\u003E - blood glucose levels are monitored by specialised cells in the hypothalamus and pancreas, not by peripheral chemoreceptors\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen activated by hypoxia, peripheral chemoreceptors trigger both increased ventilation and sympathetic activation to maintain adequate tissue oxygenation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Peripheral chemoreceptors in the carotid and aortic bodies primarily respond to decreased arterial oxygen levels.","Activation of peripheral chemoreceptors increases both respiratory rate and sympathetic outflow to maintain tissue oxygenation.","Central chemoreceptors respond primarily to changes in cerebrospinal fluid pH and carbon dioxide levels."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54153"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16866"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54153","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54153"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T10:53:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T10:54:26+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9556"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68696"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"dat